iVo has overhauled the user interface of its Virgin Media TV platform for the first time in around four years.
s well as extensive visual enhancements, the update introduces improved recommendations and content discovery services.
he menu structures have been redesigned to aid navigation, while the classic red background has made way for a plum colour scheme with refined fonts.
he Electronic Programme Guide (EPG) retains its grid layout, but now lets users move backwards through the listings and watch shows that have already aired on-demand.
"TiVo has placed emphasis on content discovery and will now recommend shows based on the user's viewing habits, and even automatically download them in the background."
 predictive search function has also been introduced, and downloaded content will be arranged into categories, such as Kids, Movies, and TV & Radio.
Under-the-hood refinements will ensure that TiVo runs quicker and offers higher-resolution imagery, and the flash-based apps it currently uses are being phased out in favour of HTML5-powered services.
More apps will also be available to TiVo customers thanks to an agreement between Virgin and Opera, which is integrating its app store into the platform.
he update will begin its rollout next month, and is expected to reach all customers by the end of the year.
Virgin Media has also updated its TV Anywhere mobile service to bring it in line with the new TiVo.
