While TiVo may be dialing back marketing expenditures in the retail segment, the back half of 2017 is looking pretty promising for us consumers.
nd, speaking of that new TiVo hardware\xe2\x80\xa6 I can confirm that, while the Mavrik initiative has been scrapped, the TiVo Mini 4K is a go. Dropping the original trapezoidal TiVo Mini form factor, the updated extender is more Roku Ultra in appearance and subtly carries forward the TiVo Bolt\xe2\x80\x99s design arc. While the headline feature may be 4K and the small number of services that have chosen to provide the higher video resolution to TiVo owners, I anticipate at least Bolt-class processing power \xe2\x80\x94 meaning it\xe2\x80\x99ll be a much more snappy and usable app platform than the legacy TiVo hardware provides and something I would absolutely upgrade for to access Netflix, Hulu, and Amazon Prime Video on Input 1 vs. flipping to Roku or Fire TV. I\xe2\x80\x99m expecting both TiVo\xe2\x80\x99s voice remote and the 4K Mini to hit this fall, along with at least one compelling new software trick\xe2\x80\xa6
