"It doesn't currently do that automatically. It offers to create a share in the installer, but it's not dynamically linked so if you change the directory either is pointing to the other isn't updated automatically. "
\nShares you use to pull video from your PC to your TiVo are managed on the Shares tab. They appear at the very bottom of My Shows with the All filter selected or in the Devices list.
"All right, the directory I'm using is the one specified in the Shares tab.  Each of my three Tivos, at the bottom of My Shows, see the other two Tivos.  If I turn on the PC running the ancient Tivo Desktop, that PC will also show up as a device.  The pyTivo PC doesn't show up.  Any thing I can look at?  Reinstall differently?"
"That's usually a firewall problem. Did Windows prompt you to allow pyTivo through the firewall the first time you launched it? You need to answer yes to that, or manually add it to the firewall. "
"\nI've also seen some complaints about it conflicting with virtual network adapters installed by VM software or VPNs. If you have any of those try disabling them. One last thing you can try is go into the settings, select the network tab, and set the zeroconf option to off. That will force it to use the old TiVo Beacon protocol which can sometimes work when zeroconf doesn't."
"It WAS the firewall.  I enabled all the pyTivo exe's and it worked fine.  I then removed them to try adding them one at a time, but Windows THEN decided to ask if I wanted to enable pyTivo in the firewall.  I said yes and it continues to work as needed.  A great tool.  Thank you for your quick replys.  I been using VideoReDo since 2010 to process Tivo recordings and it's been great fun."
