We purchase every product we review with our own funds\xe2\x80\x94we never accept anything from product manufacturers.
When it comes to the greatest inventions of mankind, sliced bread ranks right up there. The microprocessor ushered in the era of technology, and the discovery of penicillin changed the health of human beings forever. People could argue for days about which\xc2\xa0are the most important inventions in human history.
When it comes to watching TV, it\xe2\x80\x99s arguable that the DVR (Digital Video Recorder) is the best invention. Having the ability to watch television programming on your time schedule definitely makes TV more enjoyable. Pausing and rewinding sports programs\xc2\xa0to take a closer look at a play is a great option. And the ability to skip commercials is a coveted feature!
etermining which DVR best complements your television watching\xc2\xa0habits can be a little tricky.\xc2\xa0If you have a cable or satellite TV subscription, you may end up with a DVR from the provider. In such a case, you have the option of purchasing a third-party DVR and using it instead \xe2\x80\x94 this is an option taken up by\xc2\xa0many folks.\xc2\xa0After a while, all of these choices can become confusing, especially when you\xe2\x80\x99re also trying to figure out compatibilities.
"If you're ready to purchase a DVR now, check out our top five picks above. Keep reading to learn more about DVRs and which one is the best for you."
Get exclusive content, advice, and tips from BestReviews delivered to your inbox.
\n        DVRs from cable/satellite providers are often combined with a set-top box. This means you only need one box cluttering your room.      
You can rely on the product research we perform here at BestReviews. We never accept free samples from manufacturers. To compile the best information, we conduct thorough product research and interview experts and owners to find out how they feel about certain products.
We\xe2\x80\x99ve closely studied the different DVR options on the market \xe2\x80\x94\xc2\xa0fast forwarding through commercials all along the way.
Continue reading to understand how different DVRs work and which features are most important to have.
\n    Important to know: most internet streaming services don\xe2\x80\x99t allow video to be stored on a DVR.  
he market is flush with DVRs right now. Some are sold through places like Amazon, and some are available from television subscription package providers.
If you subscribe to a cable or satellite TV package, chances are the service provider has its own DVR. You could choose to use that DVR, confident in the knowledge that it is compatible with your service.
hird-party DVRs are also available. These DVRs aren\xe2\x80\x99t tied to any subscription television provider like DirecTV or Comcast. You can think of them as free agents; they work with a variety of programming options. All of the DVRs on our shortlist fall into this \xe2\x80\x9cthird party\xe2\x80\x9d category.
If you find your DVR is running out of space, you may be able to start recording your shows at a lower resolution. This will save storage space versus recording in HD resolution.
hird-party DVRs are purchased by consumers outright, whereas cable/satellite DVRs may be \xe2\x80\x9crented\xe2\x80\x9d to the consumer for a monthly fee.
ome third-party DVRs have a monthly subscription fee.
 cable or satellite TV provider almost certainly will charge you a monthly subscription to use its DVR.
In some cases, however, the cable/satellite TV provider may give you the DVR for \xe2\x80\x9cfree\xe2\x80\x9d in exchange for your subscription to their service.
ot surprisingly, cable/satellite TV providers would rather you use their DVR than a third-party DVR. So, they don\xe2\x80\x99t provide compatibility with every third-party DVR maker.
long those same lines, if you\xe2\x80\x99ve been a DISH satellite subscriber, you won\xe2\x80\x99t be able to take your Hopper DVR to your new Charter cable subscription.
In short, if you want to use a third-party DVR with a subscription package, check for compatibility before buying.
When watching live TV, the DVR automatically queues the video, keeping it in memory. You then can pause and rewind. But once you change the channel, most DVRs clear the memory queue.
ewer DVRs have quite a few valuable features that make them easier to use than ever before. If you love your TV, you will want to take advantage of these features.
VRs have a variety of ports on the back of the unit. But the easiest method of connecting a DVR to a TV is via an HDMI cable. You can connect other devices to the DVR, like an 
, through a second HDMI port or a USB port. Many DVRs have an input port for an Ethernet cable to allow you to connect it to the Internet. Some allow WiFi connectivity, too.
\n    The best way to connect a DVR to your HDTV is through an HDMI cable.  
Most DVRs offer the same types of video control options. If the video was previously recorded and stored on the DVR\xe2\x80\x99s hard drive, you can pause, fast forward, and rewind the video.
With live TV, you can pause and rewind. Fast forwarding is not available with live TV, unless you rewound or paused the live TV video earlier and have not yet caught up to current time.
If you choose a third-party DVR, make sure the remote control works with the TV as well as the DVR. It\xe2\x80\x99s just easier to keep track of one remote control.
he storage mechanism of a DVR is a hard drive, a technology similar to what\xe2\x80\x99s used on a computer. This makes sense, as digital video is basically a digital binary file, just like any computer file. The storage size of the hard drive inside a DVR varies from model to model.
Few DVR manufacturers openly advertise the size of the hard drive in their products. Rather, the size of the hard drive is listed as the number of hours of programming you can store.
\n        With some newer DVRs, you can add extra storage space by attaching an external hard drive or an old DVR to a USB port on the newer DVR.      
 DVR\xe2\x80\x99s interface includes the menus by which you\xe2\x80\x99ll pick recording options and watch your stored programs. It also usually includes a programming guide. These interfaces vary from maker to maker, so shop around to find one you like.
ome interfaces are confusing to set up and have a clunky design, while others are easy to use. The programming guide should offer a list of channels and information about each show. You should be able to set up recording directly from the programming guide.
\n    Owners of the Channel Master DVR say they love its snappy, easy-to-use interface.  
ome DVRs allow you to record one, two, or even more other programs while watching TV. This is a fabulous feature that helps ensure you never miss a show. You may need a cable/satellite TV subscription package to make it work, though. The 
VRs offer multiple recording options. You should be able to record a particular show each time it airs, either first-run episodes or all episodes. You can record the show you\xe2\x80\x99re currently watching with one button press. And you can set up a single show to record through the programming guide.
You should also be able to tell the DVR to extend the recording time beyond the program\xe2\x80\x99s scheduled end time. This is a handy feature for sports programming, just in case the game goes into overtime.
Gone are the days when you must be at home to catch your favorite shows. With a DVR, you could capture an entire season of \xe2\x80\x9coff hours\xe2\x80\x9d programming that you wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t otherwise be able to see.
ome DVRs allow you to access video streaming services directly through the DVR menus. These models contain apps that you can pick from, just like 
treaming service apps are commonly found on third-party DVRs. This is one of the strengths of the 
When comparing different DVR models\xe2\x80\x99 storage capacity, be sure that you\xe2\x80\x99re looking at storage hours in full 1080p HD resolution for each model.
\r\n\tThe hard drive is the digital data storage mechanism of the DVR. It works a lot like the hard drive in your computer for storing data.
) is the next generation of resolution at 3840x2160 pixels.
\n    One of the major differences between a DVR and a VCR is the fact that you don\xe2\x80\x99t have to manually set up recording of each TV episode on a DVR. For example, with TiVo, you can set up a \xe2\x80\x9cseason pass\xe2\x80\x9d that records all episodes of your favorite show.  
If your DVR is connected to the internet, some DVR makers will allow you to use an app to connect to it and watch your stored content from a remote location.
\r\n\tCompared to a traditional cable/satellite TV programming package, a skinny bundle is a \xe2\x80\x9creduced\xe2\x80\x9d package that costs less and also offers fewer channels. You may be able to order a skinny bundle from a cable or satellite provider. But third-party companies often offer skinny bundles via internet streaming.
\r\n\tStreaming video is the process of playing a video from the internet. When streaming through an internet connection, you download and play the video at the same time. Most DVRs cannot store streaming programming. Whether you can store streaming video on a DVR depends on the type of streaming video service you have and type of DVR you\xe2\x80\x99re using.
\n    Important to know: it is rare to be able to save video from a skinny bundle streaming service to a DVR\xe2\x80\x99s hard drive.  
VR prices vary quite a bit. You\xe2\x80\x99ll pay from 
2-Tuner
If you go with a DVR from a cable or satellite provider, you may receive the DVR for \xe2\x80\x9cfree.\xe2\x80\x9d But you probably will have to pay monthly fees to use the DVR, to receive HD capabilities, and/or to use a programming guide. Watch out for these hidden fees from cable or satellite providers.
\n        If you want to record HD programming, you\xe2\x80\x99ll need to make sure your DVR supports this type of resolution. Some low-end and older DVRs cannot record in HD.      
Q. How do I know how much space I have left to record on my DVR?
he DVR\xe2\x80\x99s manufacturer should list the total number of hours of programming the DVR can store in its marketing materials. So look on the web for this information, then apply the percentage of free space remaining to the total storage number to determine how many hours of storage remain.
Q. How do I only record new episodes of a TV show?
Q.\xc2\xa0Can I store downloaded internet video on the DVR?
\xc2\xa0Newer DVRs should be able to connect to the internet via an Ethernet cable or through WiFi. If your DVR is able to make an internet connection, you may be able to download video and store it. Whether you can store this downloaded video depends on the type of service from which you\xe2\x80\x99re downloading it and the type of DVR you\xe2\x80\x99re using.
Q.\xc2\xa0Can I use a DVR without a cable or satellite subscription?
\xc2\xa0There are standalone DVRs that work with over the air (OTA) programming. For example, the 
Q.\xc2\xa0What exactly can I do with live TV when using a DVR?
\xc2\xa0Most DVRs offer the same basic functions with live video. You can pause live TV without actually saving it to the DVR\xe2\x80\x99s hard drive. Each DVR will be able to hold the live TV feed paused in a memory queue for a specific amount of time, usually between 30 and 90 minutes. You can rewind live TV to the point where the memory queue started recording. And you may be able to save live TV to the hard drive, usually just by pressing a button on the remote.
hese are our top picks for electronics.
