Welcome to our forums! Please take a few moments to read through our 
mart TVs (LG, 2016+ Samsung, Sony, TiVo, Toshiba, VIZIO)
"I drafted a review for my TiVo Bolt.  I bought one days after they became available and have been very satisfied though I definitely have some feedback.  I thought I'd post it here and on the TiVo forums as well on some common retail sites.  Hopefully some of my constructive criticism is taken to heart by both sides to make Plex on TiVo as well as the new TiVo Bolt as great as their potential is!   Let me know what you think, thanks!"
"I had been researching a new replacement for my aging Roku2XS which has served my household well for the past few years.  The new Apple TV was not an option with no 4k support, nor was the new FireTV which seems to lack HDMI-CEC support.  Google's recent announcements did not include any updated hardware for Android TV and Roku's recent announcement for the Roku4, while a platform I know and love, also did not seem to include HDMI-CEC support.  I'm done with weird, little remotes all over the house so an included remote that could control TV volume, input, and power was a MUST.  Harmony Remotes have not worked as well as I had hoped in the past, so a unified remote was a primary function.  Basically this left me with 2 options: the new TiVo Bolt or the Nvidia Shield.  Both have most of the features I am looking for; both natively support Plex (my other absolute MUST, no side-loading please!), both had means to control everything I needed with one remote, both have 4k support, and both offer unique features that were quite appealing (gaming on the Shield and live OTA or cable TV on the Bolt)."
"The primary key to this puzzle (besides one remote to rule them all) is Plex integration.  My family uses Plex as our primary media source.  All the streaming channels I'm looking for, all the local music across my family's collections, and all the media (and home movies) that we have spent countless hours converting from discs over the years, make Plex the perfect personal streaming service.  No Unified Entertainment System solution could be complete for my household without it!  That being said the Bolt and the Shield both offer access to the latest Plex apps."
"Comparing on price I found that the Bolt was only marginally more expensive outright than the Shield, especially once you factor in a proper remote (and not a game pad) for the Shield.  There is a monthly service fee for the Bolt but that doesn't kick in until after the first year, and while more expensive than ever now, there is still a lifetime subscription option for TiVo Devices if you don't care to be nickel and dime'd every month/year.  Factor in the extra subscription costs after the first year and the TiVo is no longer comparable on price, but what you get in return is (it was in the past we'll see how I feel in a year) worth EVERY PENNY!  The WONDERFUL remote alone may well be worth the service fee for me!"
In the past I was a die hard TiVo fanatic.  I started using TiVo in the late nineties and turned many people on to their service.  I still recommend TiVo to anyone looking for a DVR solution, if it is an option for them.  To be able return to the platform has always been a dream, and now with true Plex integration it has become a reality.
"As a prior Aereo subscriber (RIP Aereo, you were ahead of your time and too good for this world) I love that I can receive OTA broadcasts through the TiVo Bolt.  Sports and local news are once again available in my home!  I have not seen commercials for many years and I am happy to report that I still (mostly) don't have to.  The new SkipMode is absolutely a game changer.  Sure there are others out there that can do the same/similar thing, but nothing with all of the other services and features the Bolt has, and nothing that will likely be around in the future (if the cable companies continue to have their way).  It does have some limitations, but when I can't use it, I LOVE that the fast forwarding  still works as expected.  I'm still an expert at landing right at the start of the show again after fast forwarding at full throttle!    I didn't realize how much I missed the bloop,bloop,bloop of TiVo's Time Shifting technology!"
"Something I was not expecting with OTA recording was recording multiple channels at the same time.  This is an expected feature when using a cable card, but for multiple tuners on OTA, I would expect a need for multiple antennas.  I guess I'm not up to speed on what's possible with digital OTA antennas as I have certainly seen multiple simultaneous recordings with only one HD antenna!  I'm not sure if all four tuners can record at once with an OTA HD antenna but I was not expecting more that one for OTA in the first place.  Kudos, Tivo!"
"Jumping back to my mention of sports, I'm not a huge sports fan.  Now, I can stand to watch sporting events, local news, awards shows and the like, thanks to QuickMode!  Watching those types of shows using QuickMode is near perfect.  Normal scripted television and movies don't always lend themselves to using QuickMode, as I usually prefer to enjoy those shows at normal speed, but the feature simply works.  One thing I notice, though, with QuickMode is that during dialog (while perfectly pitch corrected) sometimes the pauses between sentences or in a conversation between characters are so tight that it feels a little odd when you hear it.  Luckily no one will force you to use QuickMode so you can choose when it suits you!"
"The remote is still the BEST remote on the planet.  The button presses feel just right, not too hard, not too squishy.  For new users, or for people coming from other streaming OTT boxes I could see how it might be intimidating or confusing, but I honestly can't imagine it taking too long to get used to.  That perfect 'dog-bone' shape and the button layout makes for far and away the best remote control experience on the market!  From using a Roku for so long I have a terrible habit of hitting the guide button instead of the select button, kicking me out of what ever menu I was in, but I don't expect that to last much longer, though it is a pain sometimes if you're in a deep menu.  Also the improved hardware makes for a VERY snappy experience.  Button presses are instant and I never feel like the system is being taxed or the remote is lagging behind my inputs!  Such a smooth experience!  The included remote finder feature is also very welcome"
"The OnePass feature is new to me.  When I previously had TiVo it was SeasonPass and it was not yet integrated with streaming services.  The OnePass feature takes SeasonPass and one-ups it.  Some things I notice about OnePass though are as follows:  I'm not sure how TiVo is getting the listings for streaming services but sometimes their info is out of date.  Some episodes that OnePass tells me are available through streaming services are actually not and others that are listed as free or included with my streaming services turn out to be for pay or rent.  This doesn't happen often but I honestly expect better from TiVo.  We'll see how that pans out.  A huge negative for me with OnePass right now is it is not integrated with Plex.  Episodes and movies that I have on Plex are not accounted for in OnePass.  Being able to incorporate my Plex database is such a huge feature that I don't understand why it hasn't been done here with OnePass or ANYWHERE with the search functions always touted with other OTT streaming boxes!  TiVo, this is a must have with future updates!  I'm also pestering the Plex developers for this function!"
here are a few negatives to the TiVo Bolt.  Some (like OnePass issues with Plex and other streaming services, the price, and a very minor side-effect of QuickMode) have already been mentioned.  Some others are
Currently Plex is treated as a second class citizen, tucked away in the Music and Photos section or deep in the My Shows menu.  This needs to be right, front and center with Netflix, Amazon and others.  My main reason for returning to TiVo is integrated Plex.  I\xe2\x80\x99m very hopeful that this will be remedied in future updates and am banking on TiVo not being a(n expensive) detour of an OTT streaming box for me after this first year!
"The box gets warm.  Not hot, but warm.  Warm enough for the odd, though likable, shape and an inability to trust it tucked away in a cabinet.  This isn't a big deal, I just prefer an uncluttered look to my console table."
"The UI and the menus are quite busy.  This also isn't a big deal, but comparing to Roku, Plex, xBox or other 10ft UI's meant to be accessed from the couch, the TiVo UI is certainly the most complicated.  That complication offers some unique features, like suggestions on the 'home' screen and continued playback of OTA/cable/recorded (not streaming) content while in the menus.  Regardless, it's a busy UI."
"There are a few notable, yet missing, streaming content providers.  HBO Go/Now, ShowTime Anytime, Hulu, Bloomberg, PBS, and others are simply not available at this time.  This seems to be something that will be added in the future but I haven't seen definitive confirmation on which providers or when, if ever.  I already miss Bloomberg and HBO Go quite a bit.  Having a better assortment of the streaming 'channels' people want and use is a key aspect of a device such as this and something TiVo should not take lightly.  I expect more in that regard."
"External streaming is still missing.  This is a big feature that is still lacking.  In-home streaming works great through the TiVo app.  Out-of-home streaming has been promised by TiVo for early 2016.  Still, it's not here day 1."
"Speaking of the TiVo app, it is great, but for some reason it\xe2\x80\x99s very hard to figure out how to 'thumbs up' 'thumbs down' a show from the app.  Otherwise it is quite good, although, it seems to suffer from the same sort of cluttered UI as the Bolt itself.   I did have issues with the app not realizing I was on my home network and not letting me stream locally at first.  A restart of my iPad eventually resolved that."
"There is a lot of competition in the current market for OTT streaming boxes.  I think TiVo has one of, if not, the best.  While the new TiVo Bolt is definitely a recommended buy (even with it's high price), I'm forced to give 4 out of 5 stars.  There are simply too many things missing to give a 'perfect' score.  Were all the negatives addressed in this review available Day 1 I can't imagine a better Unified Entertainment System.  The TiVo Bolt it one of the first devices that can really 'do it all'.  All that's needed now is for TiVo to step up and flesh out the features that are missing.  Microsoft is looming large in the rear view with the xBox One and its rumored upcoming DVR capabilities.  I would hate to see TiVo get passed by in the near future when the technology needed is already in the Bolt just missing a little polish."
"PMS on 2011 MBP; PHT on 6 PC clients of varying OS's; Plex clients on 1 xBox360, 1 Roku, 1 Kindle Fire, 5 iPhones and 1 iPad; incredibly satisfied!"
sk me about Plex on the new TiVo Bolt! \xc2\xa0Not right now though...
his is FIXED in the Roamio! It is right there with the other Video providers now.
"Currently Plex is treated as a second class citizen, tucked away in the Music and Photos section or deep in the My Shows menu. This needs to be right, front and center with Netflix, Amazon and others. My main reason for returning to TiVo is integrated Plex. I\xe2\x80\x99m very hopeful that this will be remedied in future updates and am banking on TiVo not being a(n expensive) detour of an OTT streaming box for me after this first year!"
"Trying an update now.  Does OnePass see your Plex database?  I'll report back shortly!"
"PMS on 2011 MBP; PHT on 6 PC clients of varying OS's; Plex clients on 1 xBox360, 1 Roku, 1 Kindle Fire, 5 iPhones and 1 iPad; incredibly satisfied!"
sk me about Plex on the new TiVo Bolt! \xc2\xa0Not right now though...
hanks for the tip, I checked before I tried to update and sure enough there it is!  I checked a OnePass I have to see if Plex episodes are listed but unfortunately they are not yet.  That will be the killer integration feature.  I will update my review before posting elsewhere.
"PMS on 2011 MBP; PHT on 6 PC clients of varying OS's; Plex clients on 1 xBox360, 1 Roku, 1 Kindle Fire, 5 iPhones and 1 iPad; incredibly satisfied!"
sk me about Plex on the new TiVo Bolt! \xc2\xa0Not right now though...
iVo search does not pull movies from Plex on the Roamio. That would be nice.
I have been a Tivo user since the product was introduced.  I currently have a Tivo Premiere that provides a Plex client, but it is so slooowwww that it is unusable.  The same goes for the Netflix client.
I am interested in the Tivo Bolt, primarily to get a good experience with Plex and Netflix.  If anyone has some experience with the Plex client performance, I would like to know about it.
econdly, the Bolt could go a long way to reducing my remote clutter.  If I can get a fast and flexible Plex client, then that eliminates my RasPlex box.  If Netflix works great on the Bolt, I can eliminate a DVD/BluRay box that I now use for Netlfix access.  That could mean NO MORE INPUT SWITCHING!!!
nother question about the Bolt: the new remote is an RF device, so how do I control my IR TV power  from the Tivo remote?
Plex is the main reason I upgraded to the Bolt.  Its a great combination.  Netflix worked ok on the Roamio but is much quicker on the Bolt.  Loads in just a couple seconds and most items I have in my shows that link directly to netflix mean I do not have to navigate the netflix app at all.  Just goes straight to playing the stream.
he Tivo remote is IR and RF and should control your tv power and volume fine.
ice review. Premiere user here, 3, but appreciate the Bolt review.
