iVo officially announces its voice-controlled DVRs, the BOLT VOX and Mini\xc2\xa0VOX
iVo\xe2\x80\x99s upcoming DVR, the TiVo BOLT VOX, will include voice\xc2\xa0support
77% of consumers want a la carte TV, TiVo study finds, but price they\xe2\x80\x99re willing to pay\xc2\xa0drops
iVo Unveils BOLT, A Modern, 4K-Ready DVR Designed For The Streaming Era
We Drove Tesla\xe2\x80\x99s Crazy Fast Model X\xc2\xa0SUV
VR maker TiVo today is announcing the latest addition to its Series 6 lineup of players with the arrival of the TiVo BOLT.
he player also includes TiVo\xe2\x80\x99s popular features like OnePass subscriptions, OneSearch and support for the 
more recently launched web portal, TiVo Online
2/11,000
4K/HDMI
2.0/HDCP
802.11ac/n
2\xc3\x972
11.4\xe2\x80\xb3 W x 7.3\xe2\x80\xb3 D x 1.8\xe2\x80\xb3 H
4K/Ultra
In-home and out-of-home streaming (out-of-home in 2016)
tarting at $299.99, more expensive than streaming media players like Apple TV ($149+), Fire TV ($99.99), Roku 3 ($99.99)
till requires monthly or annual subscription fee ($14.99/mo or $149/year) but waived for year 1
Busy user interface and cluttered\xc2\xa0remote with a lot of buttons equates to a\xc2\xa0higher learning curve\xc2\xa0for new users
he most dramatic thing about the BOLT, at first glance, is the updated hardware design. Instead of a standard black box as TiVo has offered in the past, the new player is white, with a somewhat odd curve to it that initially takes some getting used to. Gone, too, are the hardware buttons in favor of integrated lights which makes the player feel more modern than the cable company DVRs it\xc2\xa0competes with.
he design itself is not only an aesthetic choice \xe2\x80\x93 the company says the gentle curve that lifts part of the player up also helps with heat dissipation. That\xe2\x80\x99s useful given the hardware\xe2\x80\x99s upgraded internals, which include a CPU that\xe2\x80\x99s three and half times as fast as the older Roamio model and three times the memory.
hese upgrades don\xe2\x80\x99t just make the TiVo BOLT perform better, but also aid with the newly added support for 4K video as well as the player\xe2\x80\x99s now built-in transcoding functionality \xe2\x80\x93 another improvement over the Roamio-S. \xc2\xa0The new BOLT will replace that device\xc2\xa0TiVo\xe2\x80\x99s entry-level DVR. Like the Roamio-S, the TiVo BOLT will also come with a 500 GB hard drive, though a 1 TB drive option will be available, too.
he other Roamio models, including the Plus (the 6-tuner, 1 TB Roamio model) and Pro (the 6-tuner, 3 TB model) won\xe2\x80\x99t immediately disappear, however. The Plus will remain in the market for a while and will \xe2\x80\x9ceventually\xe2\x80\x9d be replaced by BOLT. But the Pro, by nature of its larger capacity that doesn\xe2\x80\x99t yet have a BOLT counterpart, will stick\xc2\xa0around for the time being.
Of course, although TiVo wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t confirm this, it seems likely that the Pro will also be\xc2\xa0phased out further down the road, as having a somewhat fractured product lineup could cause consumer confusion.
he BOLT device itself is smaller than earlier Roamio models \xe2\x80\x93 33 percent smaller than the Roamio and 65 percent smaller than the Roamio Plus and Pro. It includes support for both over-the-top streaming services, over-the-air recordings from antennas, and support for recording from cable TV. That makes it a decent option for both cord cutters and cable subscribers alike, assuming they\xe2\x80\x99re in the market for an all-in-one device like the TiVo.
On the back (and bottom) of the unit are a variety of inputs, including a CableCARD slot, Coax port, optical audio out, audio L/R (analog) port, an HDMI 2.0 slot (4K, 1080p, 24/60), Ethernet, 2 USB 2.0 ports, external storage port (eSATA) and power adapter port.
Inside, TiVo has stuck with spinning disk drives, to keep the cost down, the commonly says.
he TiVo remote has also had a bit of an upgrade. While it still feels cluttered with buttons like the remotes that often come with cable companies\xe2\x80\x99 DVRs, it now has a white design and buttons for new features like \xe2\x80\x9cSkipMode,\xe2\x80\x9d a\xc2\xa0commercial skipping feature that\xe2\x80\x99s activated by pressing the green \xe2\x80\x9cD\xe2\x80\x9d button, and \xe2\x80\x9cQuickMode,\xe2\x80\x9d the sped-up playback which is engaged by pressing the \xe2\x80\x9cPlay\xe2\x80\x9d button followed by the \xe2\x80\x9cSelect\xe2\x80\x9d button.
 handy feature is a \xe2\x80\x9clost remote\xe2\x80\x9d finding function that lets you press a button on the back of the TiVo itself in order to locate a missing remote control by way of an audio sound. And the remote offers RF technology to eliminate the need of pointing it directly at the TiVo unit in order for it to work.
he remote doesn\xe2\x80\x99t include voice support like Apple TV and Amazon\xe2\x80\x99s Fire TV now do, but the BOLT itself is shipping with Bluetooth that\xe2\x80\x99s not yet turned on. That hints at a future remote hardware upgrade that could introduce a voice option.
he TiVo BOLT software, meanwhile, has also been refreshed. For those familiar with TiVo\xe2\x80\x99s look-and-feel, this isn\xe2\x80\x99t so much of a radical upgrade but more of an iterative one. There are some different colors used for certain on-screen navigational elements, flatter icons that complement the more modern design of the new unit, and channel logos now appear in\xc2\xa0the guide, for example.
What\xe2\x80\x99s more notable about the BOLT\xe2\x80\x99s software is its support for 4K, including in Netflix and YouTube apps, faster application launch times, and the\xc2\xa0new QuickMode and SkipMode features.
In addition, thanks to the more powerful hardware, apps on the TiVo BOLT can\xc2\xa0launch and resume a lot faster than before. For example, apps on Roamio would sometimes take around 10 to 15 seconds at startup, but now they take 5 to 7 seconds on BOLT. Plus, the BOLT is the only TiVo player that actually suspends the app in memory to allow for faster resumes.
iVo continues to focus on its larger strategy of allowing viewers to find, subscribe and watch content across a variety of sources, whether that\xe2\x80\x99s DVR recordings, programs on streaming services like Amazon and Netflix, or videos on YouTube. (Unfortunately, Hulu is absent from the collection of apps while TiVo waits for the company to transition to HTML5 from Flash.)
BOLT also still offers TiVo\xe2\x80\x99s \xe2\x80\x9cOnePass\xe2\x80\x9d technology that lets you instantly subscribe to shows, no matter where all those episodes are\xc2\xa0located. It\xe2\x80\x99s even improving this experience for new users with a \xe2\x80\x9cOnePass QuickSelect\xe2\x80\x9d feature that will point new subscribers via their welcome email to a page of popular shows they can subscribe to with a click.
s noted above, the other big additions for BOLT are the QuickMode and SkipMode features. The former was actually suggested three years ago by a TiVo engineer but never made it to production. Essentially, it\xe2\x80\x99s an option that\xe2\x80\x99s best used to speed up content like news or sports where you\xe2\x80\x99re trying to get information, but not necessarily looking for the traditional, lean-back TV watching experience.
Instead, QuickMode lets you watch 30 percent faster, with pitch-corrected audio.
) is a brand of digital video recorders (DVRs).  Tivo devices provides users with the ability to save television programs for later viewing ("time shifting"), an electronic television programming schedule, and recording options based on that schedule.
With SkipMode, on the other hand, TiVo is actually tagging content in a way that allows users\xc2\xa0to push a button once to move to the next part of the program without having to view\xc2\xa0commercials. This feature is live on 20 popular channels, but currently only for primetime programming (4 PM to midnight, including repeats and late-night talk shows.) Using SkipMode doesn\xe2\x80\x99t interfere with the option to use other playback functions like fast forward or rewind.
kipMode will be a BOLT-only feature, but QuickMode will roll out to other Roamio models as a software update later this year.
he BOLT\xe2\x80\x99s integrated content streaming \xe2\x80\x93 meaning its ability to stream to computers, phones and tablets \xe2\x80\x93 is limited at launch. Initially, users will only be able to view one stream in the home until November 2015 when support for two streams is added. Web streaming and in-home downloads work at launch as well, but out of home downloads and streaming won\xe2\x80\x99t ship until 2016 (the latter will only offer\xc2\xa0one stream, and arrives\xc2\xa0in the first half of next year).
he final part of the TiVo BOLT upgrade is the updated mobile app. First available on iOS in early November, with Android to follow, the new app is focused on offering users a more personalized experience. Instead of configuring user profiles, like on Netflix, customizations are per device and now include the ability for users to track their hobbies and interests in addition to genres and an expanded list of collections.
o get started, users will select from a list of hobbies and interests though an onboarding flow resembling that of Flipboard. This process then creates custom YouTube channels based on those\xc2\xa0picks. For example, if you\xe2\x80\x99re really into \xe2\x80\x9ccamping\xe2\x80\x9d or \xe2\x80\x9canimals,\xe2\x80\x9d you can add these sections to your \xe2\x80\x9cWhat to Watch\xe2\x80\x9d section.
Users can also now hide pre-configured feeds (like \xe2\x80\x9csports\xe2\x80\x9d or \xe2\x80\x9ckids\xe2\x80\x9d) if they don\xe2\x80\x99t care for that sort of content.
nd the app introduces expanded social sharing functions that go beyond Facebook and Twitter to include email and other methods. When a friend clicks a shared link, they\xe2\x80\x99ll go to the TiVo portal where they can choose to record the show (if they\xe2\x80\x99re a TiVo user) or be directed to the content itself (e.g. a list of episodes on the TV channel\xe2\x80\x99s own website).
ew Pricing: No Subscription Fees For Year One
Perhaps the most dramatic change to TiVo BOLT is the company\xe2\x80\x99s implicit acknowledgement that its current business model could be an issue going forward as more TV viewers\xc2\xa0cut the cord and turn to low-cost streaming services as their source for TV and movie entertainment.
While TiVo has focused on expanding the cable TV customer\xe2\x80\x99s experience, 
. And TiVo\xe2\x80\x99s\xc2\xa0subscription-based model can be hard to stomach for those who are looking for cost savings by signing up for cheaper services like the under-$10-per-month options from Netflix or Hulu, for example.
With the BOLT, TiVo isn\xe2\x80\x99t going so far as to ditch subscriptions, but is instead is deferring them in a\xc2\xa0way \xe2\x80\x93 a move that the company likely hopes will hook new users\xc2\xa0so they\xe2\x80\x99ll be willing to pay the fees when the time comes.
he BOLT will cost $299.99 for the 500 GB version or $399.99 for the 1000 GB version. That\xe2\x80\x99s pricier upfront than the $199.99 Roamio, which requires a subscription fee of\xc2\xa0$14.99 per month, but that\xe2\x80\x99s because the first year of service is bundled in. After year one, customers can choose to pay the monthly fee or buy an annual subscription for $149.99.
iVo Devices Now Support AirPlay For Streaming Recordings To Apple TV
iVo Now Lets Subscribers Stream Recordings And Live TV Via The Web
iVo Receives Approval To Acquire Aereo Assets
iVo Moves Storage Of TV Shows Into The Cloud With New Network DVR Service
iVo Launches Out-Of-Home Streaming From Roamio DVRs To Its Mobile App
iVo, of course, wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t exactly admit that the TV market\xe2\x80\x99s shift is potentially bad for its business, but the new product and pricing does indicate the company understands it\xe2\x80\x99s not\xc2\xa0enough to just be an upgraded DVR for the cable TV viewer. It has to find a way to appeal to those who want multi-platform viewing and over-the-air DVR functions, too.
\xe2\x80\x9cWe do a significant amount\xc2\xa0of business with the cable TV providers so we\xe2\x80\x99re not encouraging people to drop their cable subscription, but the reality is the market is a lot more dynamic than even a few years ago,\xe2\x80\x9d admits\xc2\xa0Jim Denney, VP of product marketing at TiVo.
\xe2\x80\x9cBOLT should have a strong appeal to [cord cutters]\xe2\x80\xa6you get a full DVR, all the\xc2\xa0OTA DVR functionality, and all the OTT applications that round out your content experiences,\xe2\x80\x9d he says. \xe2\x80\x9cWe\xe2\x80\x99re building it for people who have decided they\xe2\x80\x99re not going to have pay TV, but it\xe2\x80\x99s a flexible platform \xe2\x80\x93 it can satisfy both contingencies.\xe2\x80\x9d
he TiVo BOLT will go on sale tomorrow on Amazon and Best Buy and will arrive in retail channels by Sunday. Orders will be fulfilled beginning Monday.
